{{Infobox musical artist | name = Betty Willis | image = | image_upright = | caption = | background = solo_singer | birth_name = Betty Jane Willis | birth_date = {{Birth date|1941|3|10}} | birth_place = [[Mississippi]], United States | origin = [[Santa Ana, California]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|2018|1|1|1941|3|10}} | death_place = Santa Ana, California | genre = [[Soul music]], [[rhythm and blues]] | occupation = Singer, postal worker | associated_acts = {{ubl|[[Bill Medley]]|[[Leon Russell]]}} }} '''Betty Jane Willis''' (March 10, 1941 – January 1, 2018) was an American [[Soul music|soul]] singer in the 1960s.
==Biography== Born on a farm in [[Mississippi]], Willis moved with her family to [[Fresno, California]], when she was two. In the early 1960s, she moved to [[Santa Ana, California|Santa Ana]] and sang in [[Los Angeles]]-area nightclubs. Singer [[Bill Medley]], whose career with [[The Righteous Brothers]] was just beginning, was told about Willis. Medley and Willis recorded a song together at [[Gold Star Studios]], but it was never released. However, her voice and association with the studio drew notice from producers [[Phil Spector]] and [[Leon Russell]], who retooled the country song "[[Act Naturally]]" into a [[rhythm and blues]] version for Willis in 1965. As part of the duo Betty and Ray, with Ray Lockhart, she also made several other recordings. Her last known recording was in 1968.<ref name="OC">{{cite web |url=https://www.ocregister.com/2018/01/04/betty-jane-willis-more-than-another-homeless-death-she-was-a-soul-singer/amp/ |title=Who was Betty Jane Willis? More than another homeless death, she was a soul singer |last=Walker |first=Theresa |date=January 4, 2018 |work=[[Orange County Register]] |access-date=January 9, 2018}}</ref>
According to her daughter, Willis enjoyed a singing career but did not want to be part of the [[music industry]]. She also grew frustrated when paperwork was mishandled that scuttled an Africa music tour. She briefly worked in a factory before becoming a postal worker in the 1980s and retired after 37 years.<ref name="OC" />
==Personal life== Despite having family in Santa Ana, Willis chose to mostly [[Homelessness in the United States|live on the street]] in retirement. She slept outside a fabric shop, arriving after the shop closed and leaving before it opened.<ref name="OC" />
==Death== Early on January 1, 2018, Willis was assaulted by a [[homeless]] man who attempted to rape her. She was hit repeatedly on the head and [[strangled]] to death, before police arrived to apprehend her attacker. Willis was 76.<ref name="OC" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/homeless-man-charged-with-killing-60s-soul-singer-betty-jane-willis/ |title=Homeless man charged with killing former '60s soul singer Betty Jane Willis |date=January 4, 2018 |publisher=[[CBS News]] |access-date=January 9, 2018}}</ref>
