{{Infobox person |image = <!-- only free-content images are allowed for depicting living people. Non-free and "fair use" images, e.g. promo photos, CD/DVD covers, posters, screen captures, etc., will be deleted - see [[WP:NONFREE]] --> | | imagesize = 150px | | name = Gabriela Brimmer | birth_name = Gabriela Raquel Brimmer | birth_place = [[Mexico City, Mexico]] | birth_date = {{Birth date|1947|10|12}} | death_date = {{Death date and age|2000|01|02|1947|10|12|mf=y}} | death_place = [[Mexico City, Mexico]] | occupation = writer, activist | years_active = }}
'''Gabriela "Gaby" Raquel Brimmer''' (September 12, 1947 – January 2, 2000), was a writer and activist for persons with disabilities. She was born in [[Mexico City]], the daughter of Sari and Michel Brimmer, Austrian Jewish immigrants. She had a brother, David.<ref>[http://www.jweekly.com/article/full/12429/disabled-writer-whose-life-inspired-film-bio-dies-at-52/ Gaby Brimmer obituary] accessed 5/21/2015</ref><ref>[http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1988-04-15/features/8801230736_1_gaby-brimmer-mexico-city-gabriela-brimmer Gabriela Brimmer chronicle] accessed 5/21/2015</ref> Gaby was born with [[cerebral palsy]] and since childhood learned to act in a world that has difficulty accepting diversity. Brimmer's caretaker, [[Florencia Sánchez Morales]], was largely responsible for teaching her to communicate. Brimmer's life was chronicled in the film ''[[Gaby: A True Story]]''. In 1979, her Spanish-language autobiography ''Gaby Brimmer,''<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/Gaby-Brimmer-Spanish/dp/9684191014 Spanish-version ''Gaby Brimmer'']</ref> coauthored by [[Elena_Poniatowska|Elena Poniatowska]], was published by Editorial Grijalbo in Mexico City. An English version translated by Trudy Balch appeared in 2009.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books/about/Gaby_Brimmer.html?id=KxwSbEnjvPsC English-version ''Gaby Brimmer'']</ref>
== Education and early life == In 1955, she was enrolled into a rehabilitation center's elementary school where a teacher recognized her talent with words and recommended that she become a writer. In 1967, Brimmer entered a regular school. Her [[Language Arts]] teacher was a poet who also persuaded her to write. That very same year she started to write poems. The first time her mother read one of her poems she was deeply moved, cried and asked her to keep them all so that a book could be published. Brimmer could only type on the [[typewriter]] with a toe from her left foot, the only part of her body she could control. In 1971, she was accepted into the Social and Political Sciences department at the [[National Autonomous University of Mexico]] as a [[Sociology]] Major, but did not graduate.
== Gabriela Brimmer Foundation == Gaby founded an organization of people with disabilities, known as Asociación para los Derechos de Personas con Alteraciones Motoras ([[Adepam]]) (in English, Association for the Rights of People with Motor Disabilities) and was an active participant in numerous other organizations.<ref>[http://americanaejournal.hu/vol6no1/kelemen-review REVIEW OF ''Gaby Brimmer: An Autobiography in Three Voices'' by Zsolt Kelemen]</ref> Brimmer worked for the full participation of people with disabilities and at the same time managed to write poetry. Brimmer was regarded{{Who|date=November 2010}} as one who enjoyed a moving sensitivity and a strength that stemmed from the depths of her soul. Observers of her life{{Who|date=November 2010}} commented that she did not think of herself as an "outstanding personality,"{{Citation needed|date=November 2010}} even when people{{Who|date=November 2010}} could not hide their astonishment in seeing her do the things she did. She used to say, "life makes me to do it. Her message to people with disabilities was to rethink their ways of living by forgetting the limits imposed by others.{{Citation needed|date=November 2010}}
== See also == * [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B0DE2DA1F38F933A05753C1A961948260 Film: 'Gaby,' Story of Determination], New York Times, October 30, 1987. * [https://books.google.com/books/about/Gaby_Brimmer.html?id=KxwSbEnjvPsC Gaby Brimmer: An Autobiography in Three Voices.], Waltham, MA, Brandeis UP, 2009.
