{{dablink|For others, see [[John Henry Moore (disambiguation)]].}}
'''Colonel John Henry Moore''' (1800&ndash;1880) was an early Texas settler, one of the [[Old Three Hundred]] first land grantees to settle in [[Mexican Texas]].
==Early life== Moore was born August 13, 1800, in [[Rome, Tennessee|Rome]], [[Smith County, Tennessee|Smith County]], [[Tennessee]]. It is said that John Henry Moore ran away from college to avoid studying [[Latin]]. He went to [[Spanish Texas]] in 1818. (His father took him back to Tennessee, and he returned to Texas in 1821.)<ref>[http://www.tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/fmo30 "MOORE, JOHN HENRY"] in the ''[[Handbook of Texas]] Online'', retrieved 19 April 2016.</ref>
==Military career== He built [[Moore's Fort]] at present-day [[La Grange, Texas]], in 1828; but he is best known for commanding the [[Battle of Gonzales]] on October 2, 1835. He was elected a colonel of the [[Texian Army|Texan army]] and served as a member of the council of war. Commander [[Stephen F. Austin]] ordered Moore to organize a [[cavalry]] [[company (military unit)|company]], who brought their own pistols and double-barreled [[shotgun]]s.
During the [[American Civil War|Civil War]], Moore enlisted in [[Terry's Texas Rangers]]. Being 61 years old, he was appointed to a committee to help secure bonds for financing the [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] cause.<ref>''Ibid.''</ref>
==Community life== John H. Moore established the first church in [[Fayette County, Texas]], in the fort building.<ref>[https://www.google.com/search?q=historical+marker+for+%22Moore%27s+Fort%22+Texas&biw=1152&bih=769&source=lnms&tbm=isch&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjXlp2g-L7JAhUF6iYKHaDRC54Q_AUIBygC&dpr=1#imgrc=o9PRmgkaw0C5EM%3A Photo of sign affixed to Moore's Fort building], retrieved 03 December 2015.</ref>
==Death== Moore died December 2, 1880.
