[[File:Andre Rieu 2010.jpg|thumb|right|André Rieu's cameo in 2009 was named ''Neighbours''' weirdest storyline by an online poll|230px]]
''[[Neighbours]]'' is an [[Television in Australia|Australian television]] [[soap opera]] first broadcast on 18 March 1985. It was created by TV executive [[Reg Watson]], who proposed the idea of making a show that focused on realistic stories and portrayed adults and teenagers who talk openly and solve their problems together. ''Neighbours'' has since become the longest-running series in Australian television and the seventh longest-running serial drama still on the air in the world.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.watoday.com.au/entertainment/tv-and-radio/loving-thy-neighbours-20100827-13w5c.html|title=Loving thy Neighbours|last=Quinn|first=Karl|date=28 August 2010|work=[[WA Today]]|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|accessdate=10 September 2010}}</ref> In 2005, the show was inducted into the [[List of Logie Hall of Fame inductees|Logie Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvweek.ninemsn.com.au/blog.aspx?blogentryid=657831&showcomments=true|title=Neighbours – Where it all began|work=[[TV Week]]|publisher=[[Ninemsn]]|accessdate=24 May 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110520155851/http://tvweek.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=157713|archivedate=20 May 2011|df=}}</ref>

The first celebrity to make a guest appearance in the show was former [[Skyhooks (band)|Skyhooks]] band member [[Red Symons]]. He made his on-screen debut ten days after the series began in March 1985. He played the role of [[Terry Inglis]]' ex-husband, [[List of Neighbours characters (1985)#Gordon Miller|Gordon]]. In 1986, record producer [[Ian Meldrum|Molly Meldrum]] arrived in [[Ramsay Street]] to sign [[Charlene Robinson|Charlene Mitchell]] ([[Kylie Minogue]]) after hearing her singing backing vocals on a music demo. [[Greg Fleet]]'s appearance in 1988 saw him run over popular character [[Daphne Clarke]] ([[Elaine Smith (actress)|Elaine Smith]]) with his car,<ref name="Age">{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/tv--radio/more-power-to-new-neighbours/2007/08/01/1185647908705.html|title=More power to the 'new' Neighbours|last=Hardy|first=Marieke|date=2 August 2007|work=[[The Age]]|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|accessdate=25 September 2010}}</ref> resulting in her death. 1995 saw [[Chris Lowe]], one half of British music group, [[The Pet Shop Boys]], appear and ask [[Helen Daniels]] ([[Anne Haddy]]) and [[Marlene Kratz]] (Moya O'Sullivan) for directions to a studio. A year later, writer [[Clive James]] had a walk on part as a postman.<ref name="Age"/> Australian cricketer, [[Shane Warne]] made a two episode appearance as himself in 2006. He came to [[Erinsborough]] to pick up a cheque for his charity from [[Harold Bishop]] ([[Ian Smith (actor)|Ian Smith]]). ''[[Australian Idol]]'' presenter [[Andrew Günsberg|Andrew G]] made the first of three appearances by the show's stars in February 2007. Judges [[Marcia Hines]] and [[Ian Dickson (music mogul)|Ian Dickson]] followed in November 2007 and March 2009 respectively. 

During three episodes set and filmed in London, a number of British stars filmed cameos, including [[Neil Morrissey]], [[Emma Bunton]], [[Julian Clary]] and [[Michael Parkinson]]. Morrissey was the only one of the group to play a character and not himself. British comedians [[Matt Lucas (comedian)|Matt Lucas]] and [[David Walliams]] appeared as their characters, [[Lou and Andy]] and [[Tim Vine]] had a small walk on part as a lost tourist. Australian comedians [[Hamish & Andy]] made their ''Neighbours'' debut as radio hosts, Fred & Big Tommo and [[Lehmo]] had a cameo as himself in July 2010. The [[Erinsborough#Charlie.27s|Charlie's]] bar set provides a stage for musicians to perform their songs during episodes. September 2008 saw girl band, [[The Veronicas]] sing their song, "[[This Love (The Veronicas song)|This Love]]" on the set and Liverpudlian band, [[The Wombats]] sang three of their hits. Other singers and bands to appear at Charlie's, include [[Kate Ceberano]], [[Ben Lee]] and former ''Australian Idol'' contestant Jacob Butler. [[Australian Football League|AFL]] player [[Clint Bizzell]] began appearing as footballer [[List of Neighbours characters (2009)#Adam Clarke|Adam Clarke]] in a storyline that ran for just over a week in March 2009.

Dutch violinist [[André Rieu]] arrived in Ramsay Street in early April 2009. His cameo was later named ''Neighbours''' "weirdest ever storyline" in an online poll.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lastbroadcast.co.uk/soaps/features/v/8998-neighbours-weirdest-storylines-ever.html|title='Neighbours' weirdest storylines ever|publisher=Last Broadcast|accessdate=25 September 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5t0UfohuI?url=http://www.lastbroadcast.co.uk/soaps/features/v/8998-neighbours-weirdest-storylines-ever.html|archivedate=25 September 2010 |deadurl=yes}}</ref> [[World Wrestling Entertainment|WWE]] wrestler [[Dave Batista]] signed up to appear in scenes with wrestling fans [[Callum Jones]] ([[Morgan Baker]]) and [[Toadfish Rebecchi]] ([[Ryan Moloney]]), during his promotional tour of Australia in June. In the same month, it was announced that British pop singer, [[Lily Allen]], was to make an appearance and perform her new single "[[22 (Lily Allen song)|22]]" on the show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/8071502.stm|title=Lily Allen to star in Neighbours|date=28 May 2009|work=[[BBC News]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=23 September 2010}}</ref> Allen was interviewed by [[Matthew Werkmeister]]'s character, [[Zeke Kinski]], at the [[Erinsborough#Pirate Net|Pirate Net]] radio station.

